metadata.name: Pulsar #137
metadata.description:
When exploring new possibilities for a new work, I stumbled across an article on Pulsar map. Created by astronomer Frank Drake and Carl Sagan, this map serves as a galactic address of our solar system for any extra-terrestrial civilization to find using pulsars as signposts. Though chances of any kind of life form intercepting the map are slim, I'm still fascinated both by the possibility of another planetary civilization finding the map (and by extension our Earth), and the thought of using pulsar -- the remaining corpse of ancient massive star -- as universal signposts and landmarks to map the Earth position for any kind of possible civilization. To me there's something so poetic about this; it made me thinks of how small are we, the Humans, compared to those rotating pulsars that we use as mere landmarks to our location...let alone the whole universe. We are just floating stardust after all.

In this piece I use Lissajous curve array with randomized variable to position the stars and generate spline as 'star trails'. The Lissajous array is interpolated with Perlin noise array to make it less smooth and looks more random.



----------
Control:
Press [s] to capture a screenshot of the current viewport.
Press [t] to toggle the star trails (default: enabled).



Made with Cables.gl

XALTED 2022

metadata.name: Elswhere #190
metadata.description:
Perlin noise walks into a Julia set and finds itself Elswhere. X is real, Y is imaginary, or is it the other way around? 

Elswhere is a unique generative art series in which noise and fractal math are combined to create whimsical shapes and motifs, with an infinite number of variations. Made with p5js.

For each pixel, the noise values corresponding to the X and Y coordinates are computed and then used as the real and imaginary components for initializing a Julia set recursion. The pixel is colored based on the number of steps it takes for the recursion to reach its base case.

Keyboard controls:
[S] Save the current view.
[2] Render 2000x3000px image.
[4] Render 4000x6000px image.
[6] Render 6000x9000px image.

Created by Elsif, 2022.05

metadata.name: Petromyzonus #9
metadata.description:
Petromyzonus is the next creation of my Protobyte series, exploring artificial life. The creature emerges bound to the earth, but breaks free, filling the sky with generative constellations. Petromyzonus yearns for creative, human interaction; they require it to fully express their true potential (as we all do.)  

Interaction:

Mouse/Trackpad:
drag -> camera rotation
Mouse Rt Btn -> camera pan
scroll wheel/pinch -> camera zoom

Key Input:
{, }: reduce | increase X-axis wave amplitude
[, ]: reduce | increase Y-axis wave amplitude
<, >: reduce | increase X-axis wave frequency
,, .: reduce | increase Y-axis wave frequency
m, n: reduce | increase ground tether threshold
b, v: reduce | increase star tether threshold
1, 2: <<<    | >>> star rotation direction/speed
3, 4: reduce | increase creature traveling speed
q, w: stop travel | start travel
z: reverse travel direction
p: screen capture

Tip:
1. Decreasing ground and/or star tether thresholds can make grown GPU‚Äôs cry.
2. There is a hidden feature that creates a lovely painterly effect.

Please post your favorite IP.001 screen captures

metadata.name: Take Wing #87
metadata.description:
‚ÄúTake Wing‚Äù is a generative art collection depicting the hope, optimism, and thrilling excitement of a person taking off, gaining traction, and soaring to new heights and off into the great unknown.  

The algorithm behind the piece stems from an attempt to go back to art fundamentals and codify composition rules and painterly techniques into a generative form - taking into account focal points, contrast, eye movement, and color theory while still giving the algorithm freedom to explore random color palettes, random flow field movement, random brush strokes, and many other degrees of freedom.

The collection is made in pure code with p5.js and a few GLSL fragment shaders.

The piece has been created to be exhibited at "In Touch" with VerticalCryptoArt in Berlin in September 2022, curated by Anika Meier.

------------------------------------------------

To get a (somewhat) high-resolution output, open the live view of your token, and then edit the URL adding &h=5400 at the end of it.  5400 is the tallest you can go, but you can also put a smaller number if you desire.  Be aware that this will only work on a machine with a very beefy GPU, and even then may take a bit, so please be patient!

metadata.name: Until biodiversity rains #67
metadata.description:
Audiovisual generative artwork. 

In the interpretation of biological organisms, which break paradigms by doing something different, to adapt to changes and be able to survive, paths emerge to be imitated by so many, and make life flow. The development of the work is a metaphor for those paths full of ingenuity and risk, where colorful organisms in rows open trails, sliding like subtle drops, with sophisticated turns and elastic jumps.

Some alternative paths usually hide a message along the way. Literally, one could find and read phrases in relation to biodiversity and its importance. Although it is more common to ignore them, sometimes not respect them, or what is worse, forget them. Even so, in an exacerbated insistence, here, audiovisual organizations seem to be repeating themselves, ‚Äúuntil biodiversity rains‚Äù, and variety exploits so that ecosystems finally go it alone.


Relationship between visuals and sounds:
Biological organisms of different colors follow a path. They move forward, change shape, stop, turn. Always one after the other. At certain moments, they stretch and jump and sounds emerge.

Towards the edges of the canvas, the jumps are translated into cello sounds, mainly pizzicatos. Towards the center, the piano. From the main jumps emerges a kind of melody played by a pseudo-theremin-synth, characterized by flyaway melodies with glissant.


This artwork is 100% code, made in p5.js + tone.js.

[ Click ]  -> sound ON / OFF
[ s ] -> save 2160x2160px (in live view)
[ f ] -> fullscreen
[ p ] -> pause / play 

Note: This artwork is an animated piece, and requires a powerful GPU for optimal real-time playback. It is important to note that it may not run properly on mobile devices, especially not high-end ones.
It is recommended to run the piece in a new window from the ‚Äúopen‚Äù button.

metadata.name: Organicon, variation 00 - special edition #119
metadata.description:
Thank you!

Generative art by Frederik Vanhoutte, @wblut
One of 640 special edition generators creating an endless sequence of iterations with fixed features

Organicon, variation 00 is a slow piece, meant to build on the screen. A small counter in the lower-right corner displays the progress.

Interface: on first load the piece operates in active mode. In this mode an iteration is cleared 30s after completion and replaced by the next iteration. This mode is indicated by a flashing dot in the upper-right corner.

A first mouse click disables active mode. The current iteration will complete and remain on screen. A second mouse click clears the screen, loads the next iteration, and reenables active mode.

metadata.name: Miniscapes #264
metadata.description:
Miniscapes merges generative code (Rich's bit) with meticulously designed scenes and elements (Rick's bit), to create minimalist landscapes intended to charm, delight, and surprise.

Our aim was to convey as much as possible with as little as possible by using simple shapes and lines to represent a wide variety of natural landscapes.

We hope that you find as much joy in owning a Miniscape as we did in creating them.

Controls (in live view):
- Press [s] to save the current image
- Press [p] to pause an animated output
- Press [r] to reset an animated output (this will also pause)
